On the tenth anniversary of Myanmar's military takeover, exiled dissidents protested in Bangkok and Bangladesh.
The junta, led by General Than Shwe, rejected the NLD's repeated appeals for talks.
The regime threatened NLD vice chairman Tin Oo with arrest.
Britain pressured the regime to hold talks, and the US and the EU placed economic sanctions on Myanmar to encourage negotiations.
The US and some European countries boycotted the 4th International Heroin Conference there because of its drug trafficking and poor human rights record.
Myanmar has become the world's leading source of heroin and the epicenter of a regional AIDS crisis.
